definition.value: A phenylazo group in which the phenyl ring is substituted at the para position with a deprotonated sulfo group.
A phenylazo group in which the phenyl ring is substituted at the ortho position with a nitro group.
A phenylazo group in which the phenyl ring is substituted at the meta position with a nitro group.
A phenylazo group in which the phenyl ring is substituted at the para position with a nitro group.
A phenylazo group in which the benzene ring carries no other substituents; the parent of the class 'phenylazo groups'.
A chlorophyll that is the ester obtained by formal condensation between the carboxy group of chlorophyllide a and the hydroxy group of geranylgeraniol.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 2-hydroxy-3-methylbutyric acid, formed by loss of a proton from the carboxy group.
An EC 1.8.1.* (oxidoreductase acting on sulfur group of donors, NAD+ or NADP+ as acceptor) inhibitor that interferes with the action of thioredoxin reductase (EC 1.8.1.9).
An aromatic ketone that is penta- or hexaphenone bearing chloro, hydroxy and methoxy substituents on the benzene ring. A class of effector molecules isolated from Dictyostelium discoideum.

An ergot alkaloid produced by the fungus Aspergillus fumigatus that is ergoline which is substituted by a 2-methylbut-3-en-2-yl group at position 2, methyl groups at the 6 and 8beta positions, and by an acetoxy group at the 9beta position.
An optically active form of phosphatidylethanolamine having R-configuration.
A dioxo monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 2,6-dioxo-6-phenylhexa-3-enoic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A nucleotide-(amino alcohol) that is the N,N-dimethyl derivative of CDP-ethanolamine.
An anthracycline cation that is the conjugate acid of daunorubicin, arising from protonation of the amino group.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of any anthracycline.
A mannose phosphate in which in which the phosphate group of alpha-D-mannose 1-phosphate is esterified by the alcoholic hydroxy group of L-serine.
A beta-D-glucosiduronic acid that is the glucuronide conjugate of phenol.
An organic cation resulting from the addition of a proton to metronidazole.
A 1-monoglyceride in which the glycerol moiety has sn stereochemistry.
A carboxamidinium ion that is the conjugate acid of 7-formamidino-7-deazaguanine, arising from selective protonation of the imino nitrogen; major species at pH 7.3.
An organoselenium compound that is a selenium analogue of methanol, comprising a methyl group covalently bound to a selenol group.
A pyrrolopyrimidine that is 7-deazaguanine bearing a carboxamidine substituent at the 7 position.
A dioxo monocarboxylic acid that is 6-phenylhexa-3-enoic acid bearing oxo substituents at position3 2 and 6.
A sesquiterpenoid aldehyde, an intermedediate in the biosynthesis of artemisinin from artemisinic alcohol in Artemisia annua.
A carboxylic ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxylic acid group of mycophenolic acid with the anomeric hydroxy group of beta-D-glucuronic acid.
A racemate comprising equimolar amounts of (R)- and (S)-linalyl acetate. It forms a principal component of the essential oils from bergamot and lavender.
A sesquiterpenoid aldehyde, an intermedediate and reduction product from artemisinic aldehyde in the biosynthesis of artemisinin from artemisinic alcohol in Artemisia annua.
A dipeptide formed by formal condensation of the carboxy group of (3R)-3-methyl-D-ornithine with the side-chain amino group of L-lysine.
A D-alpha-amino acid that is D-isoleucine bearing an amino substituent at position 5.

The dihydroxybenzoate anion formed by loss of a proton from the carboxy group of 3,4-dihydroxy-5-polyprenylbenzoic acid.  The major species present at pH 7.3, it is an intermediate in the formation of ubiquinone.

A sesquiterpenoid that consists of (3S,4R,4aR,6S,6aS,12R,12aS,12bS)-4-(acetoxymethyl)-12-hydroxy-4,6a,12b-trimethyl-11-oxo-9-(pyridin-3-yl)-1,3,4,4a,5,6,6a,12,12a,12b-decahydro-2H,11H-benzo[f]pyrano[4,3-b]chromene-3,6-diol in which the hydrogens of the 3- and 6-hydroxy functions are substituted by acetyl groups.
An EC 2.3.1.* (acyltransferase transferring other than amino-acyl group) inhibitor that interferes with the action of acyl-CoA:cholesterol acyltransferase (EC 2.3.1.26).
A sterol O-acyltransferase inhibitor that specifically inhibits acyl-CoA:cholesterol acyltransferase 2.
A hydrochloride salt formed by reaction of equimolar amounts of trimethylamine and hydrogen chloride.
A hydrochloride resulting from the reaction of cadaverine with 2 mol eq. of hydrogen chloride.
A nucleotide derivative containing one or more sulfate groups.
A hippurate that is the conjugate base of p-aminohippuric acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
2-Pyridone carrying as substituents a branched dimethylhexanoyl group, a hydroxy group and a p-hydroxyphenyl group at C-3, -4 and -5 respectively. Secondary metabolite produced by Aspergillus spp.

2-Pyridone carrying as substituents a branched dimethylhexanoyl group, a hydroxy group and a 3,4-dihydroxyphenyl group at C-3, -4 and -5 respectively. Secondary metabolite produced by Aspergillus spp.
A thiophene substituted at C-2 by benzoyl and at C-4 by an ethyl group.
A thiophene substituted at C-2 by a 4-ethylbenzoyl group.
An organic molecular entity containing a single carbon atom (C1).
Any organic molecular entity that is acidic and contains carbon in covalent linkage.
A nucleotide-sugar whose nucleobase is a purine.
An atom or small molecule with a positive charge that does not contain carbon in covalent linkage, with a valency of three.
A phosphatidylglycerol(1-) in which the phosphatidyl moiety has R-configuration and the glycerol moiety has S-configuration.
A glycerophosphoglycerol(1-) having (R,S)-configuration.
The organic cationic group formed from L-alaninium; the major structure at pH 7.3 of the L-alanyl group, formed by protonation of the alpha-amino group.
The organic cationic group formed from L-argininium(2+); the major structure at pH 7.3 of the L-arginyl group, formed by protonation of both the guanidino and alpha-amino groups.
